by Aureumterra III » Tue Apr 06, 2021 7:14 pm

Gandoor wrote:Here's a cliché that's likely never been brought up:
NS users who come up with 'conlangs' for their nation but it's literally just them typing random gibberish that vaguely looks like it could be words with no care for literally anything that makes a language a language like: spelling/pronunciation rules, usage of IPA to help in pronunciation, fucking grammar, etymology, etc.

My nation’s "conlang" is actually technically two conlangs, although IC they’re both considered very different dialects of the same language, the rigid social hierarchy in Aureumterra and the historical connections of the aristocracy- you know I’m just going to copy the linguistics essay I wrote on discord

The Aureumterrese language spoken by the Emperor and the aristocracy is very distinct from that of the “lowborns” and the “commonfolk.” Things are further complicated by the Finns, who while having been largely assimilated into Aureumterrese society still retain a distinct Finnish dialect when speaking Aureumterrese, and Finnish itself may be spoken in some isolated areas. Icelandic continues to be spoken in Iceland despite the consistent attempts at civilizing these “barbaric peoples”

The aristocracy and ruling class speaks with more “elaborate” words, such as “Fjellöstadur” instead of “Fjell” for “Mountain,” the upper class “sub-language” also uses the eth (ð) far less, so lower classes would say “Straðokkur” while the aristocracy would say “Stradökkur.” Certain words from the aristocratic “language” are almost unintelligible to commonfolk, for example the word for “Car” is spoken by aristocrats as “Göthenkard” while commonfolk would say “Auðavot.” Basically for most of history the Aureumterrese aristocracy were weebs for Germany. Which is why the aristocratic dialects are so Germanized while the commonfolk dialect is much closer to Old Norse. For example, "Jag har bestämt mig för att landet" is the aristocratic dialect, while commonfolk would say "Ég hef ákveðið að yfirgefa landið" though they both mean the same thing


TL;DR Aristocratic dialect is based on weird amalgamation of Swedish and Danish, while common folk dialect is based on Icelandic and Faroese
